[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":802},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-15-bump\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-15-bump\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-15-bump\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-15-bump\u002F":777,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-15-bump\u002F":786},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200518\u002F1745009932\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":757,"date":758,"description":759,"extension":760,"lang":761,"meta":762,"navigation":763,"path":764,"readingMinutes":765,"seo":766,"standalone":767,"stem":768,"tags":769,"tldr":774,"updated":758,"url":775,"__hash__":776},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-15-bump.md","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (15) - Collision Detection with Bump","1001742183",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":752},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,36,50,56,62,469,480,486,616,623,717,726,730,748],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Last time we learned how to draw geometric shapes in PIXI. Now let's move on to something I think is pretty interesting in PIXI — collision detection.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"collision-detection-with-bump","Collision Detection with Bump",[17,25,26,27,31,32,35],{},"Okay, so at this point you'll probably Google around, or do what I did and dig through the PIXI API docs. And you'll find a bunch of PIXI collision-detection tutorials, all of them using ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"hitTestRectangle",". The catch is, if you try to call that directly in PIXI, you just get ",[28,33,34],{},"hitTestRectangle is not defined",".",[17,37,38,39,41,42,49],{},"Here's why: PIXI doesn't actually have collision detection built in. That ",[28,40,30],{}," is from a separate library you have to bring in yourself, and that library is called ",[43,44,48],"a",{"href":45,"rel":46},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fkittykatattack\u002Fbump",[47],"nofollow","Bump",". It packs a bunch of the 2D collision APIs you'd want. But the Bump docs mention something:",[51,52,53],"blockquote",{},[17,54,55],{},"(Important! this library targets Pixi v3.0.11, which is the most stable version of Pixi, and is the only version I can recommend using. This library will eventually be upgraded for Pixi v4 when the v4 branch matures.)",[17,57,58,59,61],{},"Basically, Bump only supports PIXI v3.0.11 right now. The author did say it'd get updated once Pixi v4 stabilized, but that seems to have gone nowhere. Luckily, a fellow contributor from the IT Ironman series shared a ready-made ",[28,60,30],{}," you can just use:",[63,64,69],"pre",{"className":65,"code":66,"language":67,"meta":68,"style":68},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function hitTestRectangle(r1, r2) {\n    let hit, combinedHalfWidths, combinedHalfHeights, vx, vy;\n    hit = false;\n    r1.centerX = r1.x + r1.width \u002F 2;\n    r1.centerY = r1.y + r1.height \u002F 2;\n    r2.centerX = r2.x + r2.width \u002F 2;\n    r2.centerY = r2.y + r2.height \u002F 2;\n    r1.halfWidth = r1.width \u002F 2;\n    r1.halfHeight = r1.height \u002F 2;\n    r2.halfWidth = r2.width \u002F 2;\n    r2.halfHeight = r2.height \u002F 2;\n    vx = r1.centerX - r2.centerX;\n    vy = r1.centerY - r2.centerY;\n    combinedHalfWidths = r1.halfWidth + r2.halfWidth;\n    combinedHalfHeights = r1.halfHeight + r2.halfHeight;\n    if (Math.abs(vx) \u003C combinedHalfWidths) {\n        if (Math.abs(vy) \u003C combinedHalfHeights) {\n        hit = true;\n        } else {\n        hit = false;\n        }\n    } else {\n        hit = false;\n    }\n    return hit;\n};\n","js","",[28,70,71,101,110,126,151,173,195,217,233,249,265,281,298,314,330,346,367,385,398,410,421,427,437,448,454,463],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,73,76,80,84,88,92,95,98],"span",{"clas